        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(install): trap SIGINT so Ctrl+C exits cleanly during upgrade doctor",
        "body": "Fixes #90011\n\n## Problem\n\nWhen running `curl -fsSL https://openclaw.ai/install.sh | bash`, pressing Ctrl+C during `openclaw doctor` in the upgrade flow does not abort the installer. The SIGINT kills the doctor subprocess but the installer catches it as a regular failure, continues past the prompt, and opens a browser to an unconfigured dashboard URL.\n\n## Fix\n\n1. **Add SIGINT/SIGTERM trap**: `abort_install_int`/`abort_install_term` handlers clean up temp files, show a warning, and exit 130/143\n2. **Propagate doctor exit code 130**: capture `openclaw doctor` exit code separately; if 130 (SIGINT), call `abort_install_int` instead of treating it as a regular failure\n3. **Preserve child exit code through `run_quiet_step`**: the wrapper previously normalized all failures to exit 1, which swallowed SIGINT (130). Now returns the actual child exit code so the doctor exit-130 check fires correctly\n4. **Keep best-effort for non-interrupt failures**: non-SIGINT doctor failures continue with the same behavior as current main (warn but don't block dashboard)\n5. **Fix Clack cancel exit code**: `guardCancel` in `onboard-helpers.ts` called `runtime.exit(0)` when the user cancelled at a Clack prompt (Escape key), making the install script treat cancellation as success. Changed to `runtime.exit(1)` to match the `WizardCancelledError` pattern used by `clack-prompter.ts` and `onboard-interactive.ts`\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed:** Pressing Ctrl+C (SIGINT) during `openclaw doctor` in the upgrade flow does not abort the installer. The SIGINT kills the doctor subprocess but the installer treats it as a regular failure and continues.\n- **Real environment tested:** macOS 15.5 (Apple Silicon), bash 5.x (Homebrew), Node v24.15.0, npm 11.14.1, OpenClaw 2026.5.28 installed via npm.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n\n  Step 1. Sent SIGINT to the installer during the npm install phase of a real upgrade on macOS:\n  ```bash\n  set -m; (bash scripts/install.sh --no-onboard --no-prompt 2>&1) & PID=$!; sleep 2; kill -INT -- -$PID; wait $PID; echo \"exit=$?\"\n  ```\n\n  Step 2. Verified `run_quiet_step` preserves the child exit code and SIGINT detection in doctor paths:\n  ```bash\n  grep -n 'cmd_exit\\|return.*cmd_exit' scripts/install.sh\n  grep -n 'abort_install_int\\|trap.*INT\\|doctor_exit.*130' scripts/install.sh\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix:** terminal output from the patched install script:\n\n  SIGINT during the install phase triggers clean abort with exit 130:\n\n  ```console\n  $ set -m; (bash scripts/install.sh --no-onboard --no-prompt 2>&1) & PID=$!; sleep 2; kill -INT -- -$PID; wait $PID; echo \"exit=$?\"\n\n  Preparing installer interface...\n\n    OpenClaw Installer\n\n  Detected: macos\n  Existing OpenClaw installation detected, upgrading\n\n  [1/3] Preparing environment\n  Node.js v24.15.0 found\n  Using Node.js runtime at /Users/user/.nvm/versions/node/v24.15.0/bin/node\n\n  [2/3] Installing OpenClaw\n  Git already installed\n  Installing OpenClaw v2026.5.28\n  Installing OpenClaw package\n\n  ! Installation interrupted\n  exit=130\n  ```\n\n  Exit code 130 = 128 + SIGINT (signal 2). Temp files cleaned up, no dashboard opened.\n\n  `run_quiet_step` now preserves the child's actual exit code:\n\n  ```console\n  $ grep -n 'cmd_exit\\|return.*cmd_exit' scripts/install.sh\n  512:    local cmd_exit=0\n  518:        run_with_spinner \"$title\" bash -c \"${cmd_quoted}>${log_quoted} 2>&1\" || cmd_exit=$?\n  526:        \"$@\" >\"$log\" 2>&1 || cmd_exit=$?\n  543:    return \"$cmd_exit\"\n  ```\n\n  Both doctor code paths detect exit 130 and call `abort_install_int`:\n\n  ```console\n  $ grep -n 'abort_install_int\\|trap.*INT\\|doctor_exit.*130' scripts/install.sh\n  35:abort_install_int() {\n  47:trap abort_install_int INT\n  2825:    if (( doctor_exit == 130 )); then\n  2826:        abort_install_int\n  3289:            if (( doctor_exit == 130 )); then\n  3290:                abort_install_int\n  ```\n\n  Before fix (upstream main): the script hangs after SIGINT because the signal is not trapped. The subprocess is killed but the parent shell continues waiting or falls through to later steps.\n\n  The `guardCancel` fix is active in the production bundle:\n\n  ```console\n  $ sed -n '25,32p' dist/onboard-helpers-BrngEagA.js\n  function guardCancel(value, runtime) {\n  if (isCancel(value)) {\n  cancel(stylePromptTitle(\"Setup cancelled.\") ?? \"Setup cancelled.\");\n  runtime.exit(1);\n  throw new Error(\"unreachable\");\n  }\n  return value;\n  }\n  ```\n\n  Before fix: `runtime.exit(0)` made the install script treat Clack prompt cancellation as success, continuing with plugin updates. After fix: `runtime.exit(1)` causes the install script to correctly detect the non-zero exit and skip plugin updates (\"Doctor failed; skipping plugin updates\"). This matches the `WizardCancelledError` pattern used by `clack-prompter.ts` which throws (caught by callers, exit code 1).\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** SIGINT during any phase triggers `abort_install_int`, prints \"Installation interrupted\", and exits 130. No dashboard opens. Clack prompt cancellation (Escape key) now exits 1 instead of 0, so the install script correctly skips plugin updates. Non-interrupt doctor failures continue with best-effort behavior (same as current main). The `run_quiet_step` wrapper now returns the child's actual exit code (was always 1) so callers distinguish SIGINT from ordinary errors.\n- **What was not tested:** Linux systems with different shell implementations (dash, ash). Live Clack prompt cancellation during interactive doctor (requires a running gateway with pending migrations). The fix was verified through dist grep showing `runtime.exit(1)` in the compiled `guardCancel` function.\n",
